---
// src/components/overlays/VenusOverlay.astro
// 9 sections — layout data-attributes drive CSS positioning.
// Sections match VENUS_SCROLL_PATH waypoints in PlanetScrollCameras.ts.

const projects = [
  {
    id:       'vesper-weather-app',
    meta:     'Mobile App · 2025',
    category: 'PROJECT',
    title:    'Vesper: A Weather App Redesign',
    excerpt:  'A ground-up redesign of a weather app\'s hourly and radar views, built around glanceability over completeness.',
    date:     '2025',
    image:    null,
    body: [
      'Most weather apps try to show everything at once — a decision that makes sense for a settings screen, not a glance screen. Vesper\'s redesign started from the opposite question: what is the one number a user actually needs in the first half-second?',
      'The radar view got the most attention: a full-screen, gesture-driven timeline instead of a cramped inset map, since precipitation timing is the single highest-value piece of information a weather app can surface.',
      'Shipped as a personal project, not client work — a testing ground for glanceable-UI patterns that later informed how the Nimbus banking redesign approached its own home screen.',
    ],
    topics: ['The Glance Question', 'The Radar View', 'Feeding Forward'],
  },
  {
    id:       'lumen-health-design-system',
    meta:     'Design System · 2025',
    category: 'PROJECT',
    title:    'Lumen: A Design System for a Health Platform',
    subtitle: 'A Design System for a Health Platform',
    excerpt:  'A token-based component library built to carry a patient-facing health platform across web and native, without the two surfaces drifting apart.',
    date:     '2025',
    image:    null,
    demoUrl:  null,
    stats: [
      { value: 62, suffix: '+', label: 'Components' },
      { value: 18, suffix: '',  label: 'Months' },
      { value: 3,  suffix: '',  label: 'Platforms' },
    ],
    body: [
      'Lumen started as a token layer — colour, spacing, and type scales shared between the web app and the native clients — before a single component existed. Getting the tokens right first meant every component built afterward inherited consistency instead of having to enforce it case by case.',
      'The hardest constraint was accessibility in a clinical context: contrast ratios, focus states, and error messaging all had to hold up for users under stress, not just pass an automated audit. Every component shipped with its accessibility behaviour documented alongside its visual spec, not as an afterthought.',
      'Eighteen months in, the system covers over sixty components and is the default starting point for every new feature on the platform — the real measure of a design system is not how it looks on day one, it is whether teams reach for it on day two hundred.',
    ],
    topics: ['The Token Layer', 'Accessibility First', 'Adoption'],
  },
  {
    id:       'solstice-rebrand',
    meta:     'Brand Identity · 2024',
    category: 'PROJECT',
    title:    'Solstice: A Full Brand Rebrand',
    subtitle: 'A Full Brand Rebrand',
    excerpt:  'A ground-up identity rebuild for a subscription hardware company — logo, type system, colour, and a guidelines deck the internal team could actually use.',
    date:     '2024',
    image:    null,
    demoUrl:  null,
    stats: [
      { value: 3,  suffix: '',  label: 'Logo Variants' },
      { value: 40, suffix: '+', label: 'Guideline Pages' },
      { value: 6,  suffix: '',  label: 'Months' },
    ],
    body: [
      'The brief was blunt: the existing brand looked like a 2016 startup, and the product had moved well past that. The rebuild started with a type pairing that held its own at both 12px UI labels and 3-metre trade-show signage — most identity work fails at one end of that range.',
      'Colour came last, not first. Locking type and logomark before colour meant the palette could be chosen to serve the system, not the other way around — a common ordering mistake that produces identities that look good in isolation and fall apart across real touchpoints.',
      'The guidelines deck was written for the internal marketing team, not for an awards submission — usage rules, common mistakes, and ready-to-use asset exports, because a brand guide nobody opens twice was not worth building.',
    ],
    topics: ['The Type System', 'Colour Last', 'A Usable Guide'],
  },
  {
    id:       'nimbus-mobile-banking',
    meta:     'Mobile App · 2024',
    category: 'PROJECT',
    title:    'Nimbus: A Mobile Banking App Redesign',
    subtitle: 'A Mobile Banking App Redesign',
    excerpt:  'A full UX audit and redesign of a mobile banking app\'s core flows — balances, transfers, and card controls — cutting task completion time by a third.',
    date:     '2024',
    image:    null,
    demoUrl:  null,
    stats: [
      { value: 33, suffix: '%', label: 'Faster Tasks' },
      { value: 4,  suffix: '',  label: 'Core Flows' },
      { value: 2,  suffix: '',  label: 'Platforms' },
    ],
    body: [
      'The audit started with session recordings, not assumptions. Watching real users hunt for the transfer flow across three nested menus was more useful than any heuristic checklist — it showed exactly where the information architecture had drifted from how people actually think about their money.',
      'The redesign flattened the navigation from four levels to two and moved the most-used actions — balance check, quick transfer, card freeze — onto the home screen itself. Every change was validated against the same recorded sessions before it shipped, not just internal review.',
      'Post-launch analytics showed task completion time down roughly a third on the core flows, with support tickets tagged "can\'t find X" dropping to a fraction of their previous volume — the kind of outcome a redesign should be judged on.',
    ],
    topics: ['Watching Real Sessions', 'Flattening the Nav', 'The Numbers'],
  },
  {
    id:       'aurora-marketing-site',
    meta:     'Web Design · 2023',
    category: 'PROJECT',
    title:    'Aurora: A Marketing Site Built for Conversion',
    subtitle: 'A Marketing Site Built for Conversion',
    excerpt:  'A marketing site rebuild for a B2B SaaS product, designed around a single conversion goal instead of a laundry list of feature callouts.',
    date:     '2023',
    image:    null,
    demoUrl:  null,
    stats: [
      { value: 3, suffix: '',  label: 'Page Sections' },
      { value: 2, suffix: 'x', label: 'Conversion Lift' },
      { value: 8, suffix: '',  label: 'Weeks' },
    ],
    body: [
      'The old site tried to say everything at once — a dozen feature callouts competing for the same fold. Aurora\'s brief was the opposite: pick the one thing a first-time visitor needs to believe, and build the entire page structure around getting them there.',
      'Every section was designed with a single job: the hero establishes the problem, the second section shows the product solving it in motion, and the third handles objections before the visitor has to ask. Nothing on the page exists without a reason tied to that funnel.',
      'The rebuild shipped with its own lightweight animation system — scroll-triggered reveals, not decoration — timed to reinforce the reading order rather than compete with it. Motion that does not serve the funnel does not ship.',
    ],
    topics: ['One Conversion Goal', 'Every Section Has a Job', 'Motion With a Purpose'],
  },
  {
    id:       'kinetic-motion-reel',
    meta:     'Motion Design · 2023',
    category: 'PROJECT',
    title:    'Kinetic: A Motion Design Reel',
    subtitle: 'A Motion Design Reel',
    excerpt:  'A self-directed motion design reel exploring micro-interactions, page transitions, and loading states — the small moments most products skip.',
    date:     '2023',
    image:    null,
    demoUrl:  null,
    stats: [
      { value: 24, suffix: '', label: 'Micro-interactions' },
      { value: 6,  suffix: '', label: 'Patterns Shipped' },
      { value: 3,  suffix: '', label: 'Months' },
    ],
    body: [
      'Kinetic was not client work — it was a deliberate exercise in the moments most products treat as an afterthought: the loading spinner, the error shake, the success checkmark. Small interactions get the least design attention and the most exposure per session.',
      'Every clip in the reel started from a real interaction problem, not a visual idea: how should a form field communicate a validation error without feeling punitive? How long should a success state hold before it clears? Motion design is a timing problem before it is a visual one.',
      'The reel became a personal reference library — several of its transition patterns later shipped, near-verbatim, in the Nimbus and Aurora projects above. Personal work at its best feeds back into client work rather than sitting separate from it.',
    ],
    topics: ['The Small Moments', 'Timing Before Visuals', 'Feeding Back Into Client Work'],
  },
  {
    id:       'halo-ecommerce-storefront',
    meta:     'E-commerce · 2024',
    category: 'PROJECT',
    title:    'Halo: An E-commerce Storefront Concept',
    excerpt:  'A speculative storefront concept exploring product-first layout and a checkout flow cut down to two screens.',
    date:     '2024',
    image:    null,
    body: [
      'Halo was never a client brief — it was a chance to test a hypothesis: most e-commerce checkout abandonment isn\'t a trust problem, it\'s a screen-count problem. The concept collapsed a typical five-step checkout into two: cart review, then a single combined shipping-and-payment screen.',
      'Product pages ran product-first, not chrome-first — the image carousel and price occupy the entire first viewport on mobile, with everything else (reviews, specs, related items) below the fold rather than competing for space above it.',
      'As a concept piece it stayed unshipped, but it is the reference deck pulled out whenever a real client project needs a starting argument for cutting checkout friction.',
    ],
    topics: ['The Screen-Count Hypothesis', 'Product First', 'The Reference Deck'],
  },
];
